@article{he2025integrating,
  title = {Integrating individualized connectome with amyloid pathology improves predictive modeling of future cognitive decline},
  author = {Hengda He and Q. Razlighi and Y. Gazes and C. Habeck and Y. Stern and Michael Paul Ronald Clifford R. William Susan Monica Oziom Weiner Aisen Petersen Jack Jagust Landau Rivera-Mi and Michael W. Weiner and P. Aisen and Ron Petersen and Clifford R. Jack and W. Jagust and Susan Landau and M. Rivera‐Mindt and Ozioma Okonkwo and L. Shaw and Edward B. Lee and Arthur W Toga and L. Beckett and Danielle J Harvey and Robert C. Green and A. Saykin and K. Nho and Richard J. Perrin and D. Tosun and P. Sachdev and Erin Drake and T. Montine and Cat Conti and R. Nosheny and D. Sacrey and J. Fockler and Melanie J Miller and W. Kwang and Chengshi Jin and Adam Diaz and Miriam Ashford and D. Flenniken and A. Kormos and M. Rafii and Rema Raman and G. Jimenez and Michael C. Donohue and J. Salazar and Andrea Fidell and Virginia Boatwright and Justin Robison and Caileigh N. Zimmerman and Y. Cabrera and Sarah Walter and T. Clanton and Elizabeth Shaffer and Caitlin Webb and L. Hergesheimer and Stephanie Smith and Sheila Ogwang and O. Adegoke and P. Mahboubi and J. Pizzola and C. Jenkins and N. Saito and K. Hussen and Hannatu Amaza and Mai Seng Thao and Shaniya Parkins and Omobolanle Ayo and Matt Glittenberg and Isabella Hoàng and K. Germano and J. Strong and Trinity Weisensel and Fabiola Magaña and L. Thomas and Vanessa Guzmán and Adeyinka Ajayi and Joseph di Benedetto and Sandra Talavera and Joel Felmlee and Nick C. Fox and Paul Thompson and C. Decarli and A. Forghanian-Arani and Bret J. Borowski and Calvin Reyes and Caitie Hedberg and C. Ward and C. Schwarz and Denise Reyes and J. Gunter and John Moore-Weiss and K. Kantarci and Leonard Matoush and M. Senjem and P. Vemuri and Robert Reid and Ian Malone and S. Thomopoulos and T. Nir and N. Jahanshad and A. Knaack and Evan F. Fletcher and Stephanie Rossi Chen and M. Choe and K. Crawford and Paul Yushkevich and Sandhitsu R Das and Robert Koeppe and Gil D. Rabinovici and V. Villemagne and B. Lopresti and John C. Morris and E. Franklin and H. Bernhardt and N. Cairns and L. taylor-Reinwald and Virginia Lee and M. Korecka and Magdalena Brylska and Yang Wan and J. Trojanowski and S. Neu and T. Foroud and T. Jo and S. Risacher and H. Craft and L. Apostolova and K. Nudelman and K. Faber and Zoë Potter and Kaci Lacy and R. Kaddurah-Daouk and L. Shen and D. Soleimani-Meigooni and R. La Joie and Konstantinos Chiotis and Maison Abu Raya and Agathe Vrillon and Charles C. Windon and Julien Lagarde and Zoe Lin and Aidyn Rose Hills and J. Karlawish and Claire Erickson and Joshua D Grill and E. Largent and K. Harkins and L. Thal and Zaven Kachaturian and Richard Frank and Peter J. Snyder and N. Buckholtz and John K. Hsiao and Laurie Ryan and S. Molchan and M. Carrillo and W. Potter and L. Barnes and M. Bernard and H. González and Carole Ho and J. Jackson and Eliezer Masliah and Donna Masterman and N. Silverberg},
  year = {2025},
  abstract = {The deposition of amyloid-β (Aβ) in the human brain is a hallmark of Alzheimer’s disease and is associated with cognitive decline. Aβ pathology is traditionally assessed at the whole-brain level across neocortical regions using positron emission tomography (PET). However, these measures often show weak associations with future cognitive impairment. A more sensitive pathology metric is needed to quantify early Aβ burden and better predict cognitive decline. Here, we aim to develop a network-based metric of Aβ burden to improve early prediction of cognitive decline in aging populations. We integrated subject-specific brain connectome information with Aβ-PET measures to construct a network-based metric of Aβ burden. Cross-validated predictive modeling was used to evaluate the performance of this metric in predicting longitudinal cognitive decline. Furthermore, we identified a neuropathological signature pattern linked to future cognitive decline, and we validated this pattern in an independent cohort. Our results demonstrate that incorporating individualized structural connectome, but not functional connectome, information into Aβ measures enhances predictive performance for prospective cognitive decline. The identified neuropathological signature pattern is reproducible across cohorts. These findings advance our understanding of the spatial patterns of Aβ pathology and its relationship to brain networks, highlighting the potential of connectome-informed network-based metrics for Aβ-PET imaging in identifying individuals at higher risk of cognitive decline. Amyloid-β peptide is a molecule that is known to accumulate in the brains of people with Alzheimer’s disease. This accumulation starts to occur many years before the symptoms of Alzheimer’s disease, such as memory problems. Current methods to image the brain for amyloid-β peptide usually measure the overall level across the whole brain. In this study, we developed a more sensitive and personalized measure of amyloid-β by also considering how the different parts of a person’s brain are connected. We found that this approach improves the ability to predict future changes in cognition compared to the standard method. Our method might enable earlier identification of people at risk of developing Alzheimer’s disease, which could improve monitoring and treatment. He et al. develop a network-based metric of amyloid-β burden by integrating individualized brain connectomes with amyloid-PET imaging. This approach improves prediction of future cognitive decline in older adults and may support earlier identification of individuals at risk of dementia.},
  doi = {10.1038/s43856-025-01170-5},
  pmid = {41350761},
  month = {12},
  journal = {Communications Medicine},
