@article{jodoin2025challenges,
  title = {Challenges and best practices when using ComBAT to harmonize diffusion MRI data},
  author = {Pierre-Marc Jodoin and Manon Edde and Gabriel Girard and F'elix Dumais and Guillaume Théaud and M. Dumont and Jean-Christophe Houde and Yoan David and Maxime Descoteaux and Michael W. Paul Ronald Clifford R. William Susan Monica Oz Weiner Aisen Petersen Jack Jagust Landau Rivera-Mi and Michael W. Weiner and P. Aisen and Ron Petersen and Clifford R. Jack and W. Jagust and Susan Landau and M. Rivera‐Mindt and Ozioma Okonkwo and L. Shaw and Edward B. Lee and Arthur W Toga and L. Beckett and Danielle Harvey and Robert C. Green and A. Saykin and K. Nho and Richard J. Perrin and D. Tosun and P. Sachdev and Erin Drake and T. Montine and Cat Conti and R. Nosheny and D. Truran-Sacrey and J. Fockler and Melanie J Miller and Cat Conti and W. Kwang and Chengshi Jin and Adam Diaz and Miriam Ashford and D. Flenniken and A. Kormos and M. Rafii and Rema Raman and G. Jimenez and Michael C. Donohue and J. Salazar and Andrea Fidell and Virginia Boatwright and Justin Robison and Caileigh N. Zimmerman and Y. Cabrera and Sarah Walter and T. Clanton and Elizabeth Shaffer and Caitlin Webb and L. Hergesheimer and Stephanie Smith and Sheila Ogwang and O. Adegoke and P. Mahboubi and J. Pizzola and C. Jenkins and Joel Felmlee and Nick C. Fox and Paul M. Thompson and C. Decarli and A. Forghanian-Arani and Bret J. Borowski and Calvin Reyes and Caitie Hedberg and C. Ward and C. Schwarz and Denise Reyes and J. Gunter and John Moore-Weiss and K. Kantarci and Leonard Matoush and M. Senjem and P. Vemuri and Robert Reid and Ian Malone and S. Thomopoulos and T. Nir and N. Jahanshad and A. Knaack and Evan Fletcher and D. Tosun-Turgut and Stephanie Rossi Chen and M. Choe and K. Crawford and Paul Yushkevich and Sandhitsu R Das and N. Saito and K. Hussen and Ozioma Okonkwo and Hannatu Amaza and Mai Seng Thao and Matt Glittenberg and Isabella Hoàng and J. Strong and Trinity Weisensel and Fabiola Magaña and L. Thomas and K. Germano and Sandra Talavera and Vanessa Guzmán and Adeyinka Ajayi and J. Benedetto and Shaniya Parkins and Omobolanle Ayo and V. Villemagne and B. Lopresti and Robert Koeppe and Gil D. Rabinovici and John C. Morris and E. Franklin and N. Cairns and L. taylor-Reinwald and Virginia M.-Y. Lee and M. Korecka and Magdalena Brylska and Yang Wan and J. Trojanowki and S. Neu and T. Foroud and T. Jo and S. Risacher and H. Craft and L. Apostolova and K. Nudelman and K. Faber and ZoA Potter and Kaci Lacy and R. Kaddurah-Daouk and L. Shen and D. Soleimani-Meigooni and R. La Joie and Konstantinos Chiotis and Maison Abu Raya and Agathe Vrillon and Charles C. Windon and Julien Lagarde and Zoe Lin and Aidyn Rose Hills and J. Karlawish and E. Largent and K. Harkins and Joshua D Grill and Zaven Kachaturian and Richard Frank and Peter J. Snyder and N. Buckholtz and John K. Hsiao and Laurie Ryan and S. Molchan and M. Carrillo and W. Potter and L. Barnes and H. González and Carole Ho and J. Jackson and Eliezer Masliah and Donna Masterman and N. Silverberg},
  year = {2025},
  abstract = {Over the years, ComBAT has become the standard method for harmonizing MRI-derived measurements, with its ability to compensate for site-related additive and multiplicative biases while preserving biological variability. However, ComBAT relies on a set of assumptions that, when violated, can result in flawed harmonization. In this paper, we thoroughly review ComBAT’s mathematical foundation, outlining these assumptions, and exploring their implications for the demographic composition necessary for optimal results. Through a series of experiments involving a slightly modified version of ComBAT called Pairwise-ComBAT tailored for normative modeling applications, we assess the impact of various population characteristics, including population size, age distribution, the absence of certain covariates, and the magnitude of additive and multiplicative factors. Based on these experiments, we present five essential recommendations that should be carefully considered to enhance consistency and supporting reproducibility, two essential factors for open science, collaborative research, and real-life clinical deployment.},
  doi = {10.1038/s41598-025-25400-x},
  pmid = {41285828},
  month = {11},
  journal = {Scientific Reports},
  volume = {15},
  google_scholar_id = {x-a4f8wAAAAJ},
  altmetric = {true},
  dimensions = {true},
  note = {Cited by 2},
}

