elden and A. Atri and K. A. Clark and E. Zamrini and Marwan Sabbagh and R. Killiany and R. Stern and Jesse Mez and Neil W. Kowall and A. Budson and T. Obisesan and Oyonumo E. Ntekim and S. Wolday and J. Khan and E. Nwulia and Sheeba Nadarajah and Alan J. Lerner and P. Ogrocki and C. Tatsuoka and P. Fatica and P. Maillard and J. Olichney and O. Carmichael and V. Bates and H. Capote and M. Rainka and M. Borrie and T. Lee and Dr Rob Bartha and S. Johnson and Sanjay Asthana and C. Carlsson and A. Perrin and A. Burke and D. Scharre and M. Kataki and R. Tarawneh and D. Hart and E. Zimmerman and D. Celmins and Delwyn D. Miller and Laura L. BolesPonto and K. Smith and H. Koleva and H. Shim and K. W. Nam and Susan K. Schultz and J. Williamson and S. Craft and J. Cleveland and Mia Yang and K. Sink and B. Ott and J. Drake and G. Tremont and L. Daiello and J. Drake and Aaron Ritter and C. Bernick and D. Munic and Abigail O’Connelll and Jacobo Mintzer and A. Wiliams and J. Masdeu and Jiong Shi and Angelica Garcia and P. Newhouse and S. Potkin and S. Salloway and P. Malloy and S. Correia and S. Kittur and Godfrey D. Pearlson and K. Blank and K. Anderson and L. Flashman and M. Seltzer and M. Hynes and R. Santulli and N. Relkin and Gloria C. Chiang and Athena Lee and Michael P. Lin and L. Ravdin and Ron Petersen and Thomas Neylan and J. Grafman and Sarah Danowski and Catherine Nguyen-Barrera and J. Hayes and Shannon Finley and M. Bernstein and M. Senjem and Normal L. Foster and Sungeun Kim and Ajay Sood and K. Blanchard and Debra A. Fleischman and K. Arfanakis and D. Varon and Maria T. Greig and J. Petrella and B. Goldstein and K. Martin and Christopher Reist and C. Sadowsky and Walter Martínez and Teresa Villena and H. Rosen and G. Marshall and E. R. Peskind and E. Petrie and Gail Li and S. Mackin and G. Jimenez-Maggiora and Erin Drake and Michael C. Donohue and Craig Nelson and David Bickford and Meryl A. Butters and M. Zmuda and Denise A. Reyes and K. Faber and K. Nudelman and Yiu Ho Au and K. Scherer and Daniel Catalinotto and Samuel Stark and Elise Ong and Dariella Fernandez},
  year = {2023},
  abstract = {Summary Background Deep learning has shown potential in various scientific domains but faces challenges when applied to complex, high-dimensional multi-omics data. Alzheimer's Disease (AD) is a neurodegenerative disorder that lacks targeted therapeutic options. This study introduces the Circular-Sliding Window Association Test (c-SWAT) to improve the classification accuracy in predicting AD using serum-based metabolomics data, specifically lipidomics. Methods The c-SWAT methodology builds upon the existing Sliding Window Association Test (SWAT) and utilizes a three-step approach: feature correlation analysis, feature selection, and classification. Data from 997 participants from the Alzheimer's Disease Neuroimaging Initiative (ADNI) served as the basis for model training and validation. Feature correlations were analyzed using Weighted Gene Co-expression Network Analysis (WGCNA), and Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN) were employed for feature selection. Random Forest was used for the final classification. Findings The application of c-SWAT resulted in a classification accuracy of up to 80.8% and an AUC of 0.808 for distinguishing AD from cognitively normal older adults. This marks a 9.4% improvement in accuracy and a 0.169 increase in AUC compared to methods without c-SWAT. These results were statistically significant, with a p-value of 1.04 × 10ˆ-4. The approach also identified key lipids associated with AD, such as Cer(d16:1/22:0) and PI(37:6). Interpretation Our results indicate that c-SWAT is effective in improving classification accuracy and in identifying potential lipid biomarkers for AD. These identified lipids offer new avenues for understanding AD and warrant further investigation. Funding The specific funding of this article is provided in the acknowledgements section.},
