de Santi and P. Doraiswamy and J. Petrella and T. Wong and C. Clark and S. Arnold and J. Karlawish and David A. Wolk and Charles D. Smith and G. Jicha and Peter Hardy and P. Sinha and Elizabeth Oates and G. Conrad and O. Lopez and M. Oakley and D. Simpson and A. Porsteinsson and B. Goldstein and K. Martin and K. Makino and M. Ismail and C. Brand and R. Mulnard and G. Thai and Catherine McAdams-Ortiz and K. Womack and D. Mathews and M. Quiceno and Ramon Diaz‐Arrastia and Richard D. King and Myron Weiner and K. M. Cook and M. Devous and A. Levey and J. Lah and J. Cellar and J. Burns and H. Anderson and R. Swerdlow and L. Apostolova and K. Tingus and E. Woo and D. Silverman and P. Lu and G. Bartzokis and N. Graff-Radford and F. Parfitt and Tracy Kendall and Heather K. Johnson and M. Farlow and A. Hake and B. Matthews and S. Herring and Cynthia Hunt and C. V. van Dyck and R. Carson and M. MacAvoy and H. Chertkow and H. Bergman and C. Hosein and S. Black and B. Stefanovic and Curtis Caldwell and G. Hsiung and H. Feldman and B. Mudge and M. Assaly and A. Kertesz and J. Rogers and C. Bernick and D. Munic and D. Kerwin and M. Mesulam and K. Lipowski and Chuang‐Kuo Wu and N. Johnson and C. Sadowsky and Walter Martínez and Teresa Villena and Raymond Scott Turner and K. Johnson and B. Reynolds and R. Sperling and K. Johnson and G. Marshall and Meghan T. Frey and J. Yesavage and Joy Taylor and B. Lane and A. Rosen and J. Tinklenberg and M. Sabbagh and C. Belden and S. Jacobson and Sherye A. Sirrel and N. Kowall and R. Killiany and A. Budson and A. Norbash and P. L. Johnson and T. Obisesan and S. Wolday and Joanne S. Allard and A. Lerner and P. Ogrocki and Leon Hudson and E. Fletcher and Owen Carmichael and J. Olichney and S. Kittur and M. Borrie and T. Lee and R. Bartha and Sterling C. Johnson and S. Asthana and C. Carlsson and S. Potkin and Adrian Preda and D. Nguyen and P. Tariot and Stephanie A. Reeder and V. Bates and H. Capote and M. Rainka and D. Scharre and M. Kataki and Anahita Adeli and E. Zimmerman and D. Celmins and Alice D. Brown and G. Pearlson and K. Blank and K. Anderson and R. Santulli and T. Kitzmiller and E. Schwartz and K. Sink and J. Williamson and P. Garg and F. Watkins and Brian L. Ott and H. Querfurth and G. Tremont and S. Salloway and P. Malloy and S. Correia and H. Rosen and B. Miller and J. Mintzer and K. Spicer and D. Bachman and E. Finger and S. Pasternak and I. Rachinsky and D. Drost and N. Pomara and R. Hernando and A. Sarrael and S. Schultz and L. L. Boles Ponto and H. Shim and Karen E. Smith and N. Relkin and G. Chiang and L. Ravdin and Amanda G. Smith and K. Fargher and B. A. Raj and David A. Wolk and I. Nasrallah},
  year = {2022},
  abstract = {Alzheimer’s disease (AD) is defined by amyloid (A) and tau (T) pathologies, with T better correlated to neurodegeneration (N). However, T and N have complex regional relationships in part related to non-AD factors that influence N. With machine learning, we assessed heterogeneity in 18F-flortaucipir vs. 18F-fluorodeoxyglucose positron emission tomography as markers of T and neuronal hypometabolism (NM) in 289 symptomatic patients from the Alzheimer’s Disease Neuroimaging Initiative. We identified six T/NM clusters with differing limbic and cortical patterns. The canonical group was defined as the T/NM pattern with lowest regression residuals. Groups resilient to T had less hypometabolism than expected relative to T and displayed better cognition than the canonical group. Groups susceptible to T had more hypometabolism than expected given T and exhibited worse cognitive decline, with imaging and clinical measures concordant with non-AD copathologies. Together, T/NM mismatch reveals distinct imaging signatures with pathobiological and prognostic implications for AD. In Alzheimer’s disease (AD) tau and neurodegeneration have complex regional relationships. Here, the authors show neuronal hypometabolism discordant with tau burden defines functional resilience or susceptibility to Alzheimer’s pathology via limbic/cortical axes. Susceptible groups have faster cognitive decline and evidence of non-Alzheimer’s pathologies.},
  doi = {10.1038/s41467-022-28941-1},
  pmid = {35314672},
  month = {03},
  journal = {Nature Communications},
  volume = {13},
